{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2013}} [[File:Karl Wilhelm Diefenbach Selbstbildnis 1895.jpg|thumb|240px|''Self-Portrait Before Easel'', 1895, oil on canvas, 119 × 60,5 cm, [[Jack Daulton]] Collection, Los Altos Hills, California<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.symbolismus.com|title=Symbolismus, Symbolismus Home|website=www.symbolismus.com|access-date=2017-02-18}}</ref> ]] [[File:Karl Wilhelm Diefenbach Frage an die Sterne 1898.jpg|thumb|240px|''Frage an die Sterne'' (Asking the Stars), 1898.]] '''Karl Wilhelm Diefenbach''' (February 21, 1851, – December 15, 1913) was a [[List of German painters|German painter]] and [[social reformer]].
==Life==
Diefenbach was born at [[Hadamar]], then part of the [[Duchy of Nassau]].
He was a pioneer of the [[naturism|naturist]] and the [[peace movement]]s. His country [[commune]], Himmelhof, in Ober Sankt Veit near [[Vienna]] (1897–1899) was one of the models for the reform settlement ''[[Monte Verità]]'' in [[Ascona]].<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.gusto-graeser.info/Diefenbach/ | title=Himmelhof. Urzelle der Alternativbewegung, 1897-1899 | publisher=Umbruch-Verlag | author=Müller, Hermann | year=2011 | location=Recklinghausen | pages=210 | isbn=978-3-937-72608-3}}</ref> His ideas included life in harmony with nature and rejection of [[monogamy]], turning away from any [[religion]] (although he was a follower of [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|theosophy]]), and a [[vegetarian]] diet.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.capri.net/en/famous-visitors | title=The writers, artists and aristocrats who fell in love with Capri | publisher=Capri.Net | work=Karl Wilhelm Diefenbach (Hadamar 1851 - Capri, 1913) | accessdate=30 November 2013}}</ref> <!--One of his students was the artist [[Konstantinos Parthenis]].--> When his commune went bankrupt, he moved to [[Capri]] and stayed there for until his death in 1913
As a painter, Diefenbach was an independent representative of [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolism]]. There has been a museum of his works in [[Certosa di San Giacomo]] on Capri since 1974.<ref>[http://www.incampania.com/en/beniculturali.cfm?s=5&Menu_ID=211&Sub_ID=213&Info_ID=4424 in Campania: Certosa di San Giacomo – Museo Diefenbach] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713022955/http://www.incampania.com/en/beniculturali.cfm?s=5&Menu_ID=211&Sub_ID=213&Info_ID=4424 |date=13 July 2011 }}. Retrieved 30 November 2013.</ref>
